Kowloon's Black Ledger includes the Passage Tithe as the historical precursor to its current cargo-assessment levy system.
The Neon Covenant's levy structure was developed partly by analyzing what the Tithe got right and what it got wrong.
What it got right: payment-in-kind maintains trade flow when coin fails; transit certification creates a cross-network pass that reduces redundant assessment; a fraction-of-cargo standard scales automatically with cargo value.
What it got wrong: the collection network's coherence was more fragile than the coin system it replaced; without a single authority backing the transit certifications, fragmentation was inevitable.
Kowloon's response: the Neon Covenant's levy system requires that all collection points honor transit certifications issued at any other Kowloon-recognized point.
This mutual recognition requirement is explicitly cited in Covenant documentation as the lesson drawn from the Tithe's fragmentation failure.
The requirement is enforced through the Black Ledger's audit function: collection points that refuse valid certifications are documented and their own certifications are downgraded.
Kowloon's assessment of the Tithe: it was a correct response to an impossible situation. It failed because cross-network trust is harder to maintain than the goods it was meant to move.
Building the trust structure before the crisis is the lesson. The Tithe built it during the crisis, which was too late.

