Kiess's route law includes a Tithe-derived clause governing emergency payment arrangements for caravan operators who cannot provide coin at frontier collection points.
The clause is called the survival tariff: a certified caravan in documented distress may pay a fraction of cargo rather than coin at any Kiess-licensed collection point.
The survival tariff is not charity: the caravan still pays, the collection point still receives value, and the transit certification is issued normally.
It is crisis accommodation: the payment form changes to preserve route function when the standard form is unavailable.
Kiess's anti-secrecy doctrine required full disclosure of the survival tariff's terms: what distress qualifies, what fractions apply by cargo type, and what documentation the caravan must provide.
The transparency is functional: if caravan operators do not know the survival tariff exists, they will not use it; if they do not know its terms, they will not qualify correctly.
The Evermeet lesson applied to the Tithe: the Tithe's fragmentation was partly caused by operators not knowing which certifications were valid at which collection points.
Public disclosure of all certification terms and mutual recognition lists prevents exactly this confusion.
Kiess publishes its active mutual recognition agreements quarterly. Collection points that have been delisted from recognition are also disclosed with the reason for delisting.

