Deltari in Kowloon maintain oral records of the Passage Tithe's operation in the delta region that predate Kowloon's administrative records of the same period.
The Deltari records provide the most detailed surviving account of how the Tithe functioned at the lower end of the cargo scale: small-boat operators, reed traders, and seasonal fish-cargo routes.
These operators were affected by the Tithe differently than overland caravans: their cargo was perishable, their route distances were shorter, and their payment-in-kind options were fewer.
A caravan can pay a fraction of grain. A reed boat cannot pay a fraction of fish: the fish will be dead before redistribution is complete.
Deltari records document the local adaptations that emerged: Tithe collection points near the delta accepted preservation work rather than cargo fraction — salting, drying, and storage services in lieu of cargo.
This service-payment variant was not part of the Tithe's formal design. It was improvised by Deltari collection officers and later acknowledged by Kowloon's administrative records as locally valid.
Deltari in Kowloon cite this case in Reed Law advocacy: the Tithe's formal design was inadequate for aquatic trade realities; the practical solution was developed by the people who actually worked the water.
Kowloon's current levy system includes a service-payment option for perishable cargo routes that traces its form directly to the Deltari delta adaptation.
The adaptation is acknowledged in Kowloon's documentation. The Deltari origin of the adaptation is not. Deltari in Kowloon's administrative system are working to add the attribution.
